  "meta_description": "Urgent news: A quarter of UK councils will miss the deadline for implementing mandatory food waste collections. Find out if your local authority is affected.",
  "summary_30w": "A quarter of UK councils will miss the upcoming deadline for mandatory food waste collections, disrupting recycling efforts. Residents must act now to prepare.",
  "article": "In a concerning development, a new report has revealed that one in four councils in the UK will fail to meet the upcoming deadline for implementing mandatory food waste collections. This looming deadline, set by the government, aims to improve recycling rates and reduce the environmental impact of food waste across the country. 

However, with just months to go before the cutoff, many local authorities are struggling to put the necessary infrastructure and collection services in place. This will leave millions of households without access to food waste recycling, undermining national efforts to tackle the growing food waste crisis.

The report, compiled by industry experts, found that 25% of councils are on track to miss the deadline, which falls in 2023. This means that an estimated 8 million homes will be left without a dedicated food waste collection service, despite the legal requirement. 

The reasons behind the delays are varied, with some councils citing budget constraints, logistical challenges, and difficulties sourcing the necessary equipment and vehicles. Others have struggled to educate and engage residents on the importance of food waste recycling, a crucial component of the new mandate.

