At the heart of the dispute are the FCC's new rules, which require drone manufacturers to implement additional radio frequency (RF) identification capabilities in their products. The FCC argues that these measures are necessary to enhance drone safety and security, but DJI contends that the regulations are overly burdensome and fail to consider the company's existing safety features and compliance efforts.

'DJI has consistently demonstrated its commitment to safety and security, and we have worked closely with regulators to develop solutions that address their concerns,' said a DJI spokesperson. 'However, the FCC's latest actions go far beyond what is necessary and will stifle innovation, increase costs for consumers, and jeopardize the continued growth of the drone industry.'

The lawsuit alleges that the FCC's rules were developed without proper consideration of the technical and economic impacts on drone manufacturers like DJI. The company claims that the new requirements will force it to redesign its products, leading to significant delays and increased costs that will ultimately be passed on to consumers.

'The FCC has carelessly implemented these regulations without fully understanding the implications for the drone industry,' the DJI spokesperson added. 'We are taking legal action to protect our ability to continue innovating and providing our customers with the high-quality, safe, and secure drone technology they have come to expect from DJI.'

