The dark bee, also known as the European dark bee or Apis mellifera mellifera, is a subspecies native to Northern and Central Europe. Historically, it was the dominant bee across the continent, playing a vital role in pollinating a wide range of plants, from wildflowers to important agricultural crops. However, the species has faced numerous threats, including habitat loss, pesticide use, and competition from non-native bee species.

In recent years, conservation efforts have focused on protecting the remaining dark bee populations and facilitating their recovery. A key part of this strategy is the annual 'wedding flight,' a remarkable natural phenomenon that takes place across Europe each summer.

The ritual begins when the virgin queens, which have been developing in their hives over the winter, emerge simultaneously on a warm, sunny day. Guided by pheromones and an innate sense of timing, the queens take to the skies, forming large swarms that can be seen for miles.

As the queens fly, male drones from nearby hives join the swarm, drawn by the queens' scent. The drones then compete to mate with the queens, engaging in a complex aerial dance as they vie for the chance to pass on their genetic material. This mating ritual can last for hours, with the successful drones falling to the ground spent, while the mated queens break off to establish new colonies.

The synchronization of this event is crucial, as it ensures a high rate of successful mating and the establishment of new hives. By concentrating the mating process into a single, coordinated event, the dark bee population is able to rebound more effectively, with the new queens dispersing to found colonies across the region.

