Analysts say the US move is part of a broader strategy to ratchet up pressure on the Cuban government, which Washington has long accused of human rights abuses and political repression. However, Caribbean leaders argue that this approach is counterproductive and risks further destabilizing the region.

'We've seen this playbook before, and it has never worked,' said the Prime Minister of Antigua and Barbuda, Gaston Browne. 'Isolation and economic strangulation have only served to empower hardliners in Cuba and undermine the very democratic reforms we seek to encourage.'

Caribbean nations have a long history of navigating the complex geopolitics of the region, often serving as intermediaries between the US and Cuba. Now, they find themselves in a delicate position, urging both sides to step back from the brink and engage in constructive dialogue.

